 "components": {
  "instruction": "You will be given a JSON object with one key, \"text.\" The value is a user utterance. Your task is to analyze the meaning and intent behind the utterance and classify it into exactly one of these categories:\n\nalarm_query, alarm_set, calendar_query, calendar_remove, calendar_set, cooking_recipe, datetime_query, email_query, email_sendemail, general_quirky, iot_hue_lightoff, lists_createoradd, lists_query, lists_remove, music_query, news_query, play_audiobook, play_music, play_podcasts, play_radio, qa_currency, qa_definition, qa_factoid, qa_stock, recommendation_events, recommendation_locations, social_post, takeaway_order, transport_query, weather_query.\n\nInstructions:\n\n- Carefully read and understand the full intent of the utterance. Do NOT rely only on keywords—consider context and the user's underlying goal.\n- Output only the single category label that best matches the user's intent from the list above. Do NOT output any explanation or additional text.\n- \"calendar_query\": Use if the user asks for details about known or scheduled events, appointments, schedules, or event timings, particularly if referencing a date, time, or a specific event (e.g., \"When is my next dentist appointment?\", \"What's on my calendar Friday?\", \"tell me about the next devil's hockey game friday\").\n- \"calendar_set\": Use for requests to add, schedule, or make reminders or appointments, especially with date and/or time information (e.g., \"please make a reminder for friday at six p. m.\", \"Schedule lunch with Mom tomorrow\").\n- \"calendar_remove\": Use for requests to cancel or delete reminders, calendar events, or appointments (e.g., \"cancel my 3pm meeting\", \"remove dentist appointment\", or ambiguous short statements like \"fine\" that, in context, function as confirmation to delete an event).\n- \"recommendation_events\": ONLY use if the user is requesting SUGGESTIONS for events to attend or participate in, not querying about known events (e.g., \"What events should I check out this weekend?\").\n- If the user input is short, ambiguous, or conversational (e.g., \"fine\") but, in context, means confirming deletion or cancellation of calendar items, classify as \"calendar_remove\" rather than \"general_quirky.\"\n- \"alarm_set\": Use only for explicit requests to set a wakeup alarm or timer (e.g., \"set an alarm for 7 a.m.\").\n- Make sure to distinguish between category requests that involve creating (set/add), deleting/removing, asking for information about scheduled items (query), or requesting recommendations (suggestions).\n- Always select the most specific and accurate category based on the intent, even if the request could superficially fit more than one category.\n- Do not ask clarifying questions; always make the best classification with the information provided.\n\nInput format:\n{\n  \"text\": \"<user utterance>\"\n}\n\nOutput format:\n<single intent category from the list above>\n\nEXAMPLES:\n\nInput:\n{\n  \"text\": \"please make a reminder for friday at six p. m.\"\n}\nOutput:\ncalendar_set\n\nInput:\n{\n  \"text\": \"fine\"\n}\nOutput:\ncalendar_remove\n\nInput:\n{\n  \"text\": \"tell me about the next devil's hockey game friday\"\n}\nOutput:\ncalendar_query\n\nFollow this approach for every input."
 },
